record_data.record_plain_text: FERC RATE SCHEDULE NO. 1 1. Availability: Seller makes electric energy and/or capacity available under this Rate Schedule for wholesale sales to any purchasers for resale. Seller also makes available to any purchaser ancillary services listed in this Section 1. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (“PJM”) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (“CAISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. Third-Party Ancillary Services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider’s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 2. Applicability: This Rate Schedule is applicable to all wholesale sales of electric energy, capacity and/or ancillary services by Seller not otherwise expressly subject to another rate schedule of Seller. 3. Rates: All sales under this Rate Schedule shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Other Terms and Condition: All other terms and conditions for any sales under this Rate Schedule shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 5. Effective Date: This Rate Schedule shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 6. Compliance With Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller’s market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller’s market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller’s market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff. 7. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Seller has no additional limitations on its market-based rate authority. The Commission has granted Seller (i) waiver of the accounting and reporting requirements contained in 18 C.F.R. Parts 41, 101 (with the exception that waiver of the provisions that apply to hydropower licensees has not been granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects), and 141, except Sections 141.14 and 141.15; (ii) waiver of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subparts B and C, except Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16; and (iii) blanket authorization for the issuance of securities or the assumption of liabilities pursuant to 18 C.F.R. Part 34. H.A. Wagner LLC, Docket No. ER12-2512-000 (2012). 8. Seller Category: Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Northeast Region and a Category 1 seller in all other regions, as defined in 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a).

?H.A. WAGNER LLC RELIABILITY MUST RUN CONTINUING OPERATIONS RATE SCHEDULE
Pursuant to the rates, terms, and conditions of this Reliability Must Run Continuing Operations Rate Schedule (“Rate Schedule”), H.A. Wagner LLC (“H.A. Wagner”) will continue to own, operate, and maintain H.A. Wagner Units 3 and 4 for the purpose of facilitating the reliable operation of the PJM Transmission System. 1. DEFINITIONS 1.1. “Base Residual Auction” shall have the meaning provided to such term in the PJM Tariff. 1.2. “H.A. Wagner Generating Station” shall mean H.A. Wagner Unit 3 and H.A. Wagner Unit 4. 1.3. “H.A. Wagner Unit 3” shall mean Unit 3 of the H.A. Wagner Generating Station. 1.4. “H.A. Wagner Unit 4” shall mean Unit 4 of the H.A. Wagner Generating Station. 1.5. “Capacity Market Revenues” means any revenues received by or due to the administrative MW-equivalent of H.A. Wagner as a result of one or both Units clearing or being cleared, in whole or in part, in a Base Residual Auction and/or Incremental Action. 1.6. “Consumables” means chemicals and bulk lubricating oils procured, retained, or produced, as applicable, to provide service pursuant to this Rate Schedule. 1.7. “Delivery Year” shall have the meaning provided to such term in the PJM Tariff. 1.8. “Effective Date” shall mean the effective date given to this Rate Schedule by FERC. 1.9. “FERC” shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or its successor. 1.10. “Force Majeure” means an event or circumstance which prevents H.A. Wagner from performing all or part of its obligations under this Rate Schedule, which event or circumstance was not anticipated as of the date of filing this Rate Schedule with FERC, which is not within the reasonable control of, or the result of the negligence of, H.A. Wagner, and which, by the exercise of due diligence, H.A. Wagner is unable to overcome or avoid or cause to be avoided. 1.11. “Incremental Auction” shall have the meaning provided to such term in the PJM Tariff. 1.12. “Markets Gateway” means PJM’s tool for market participants to use to submit resource energy offers, ancillary services markets offers, demand bids, resource intra-day/intra-hour status and parameter updates in the Day-Ahead, Real-Time and Ancillary Services markets, as well as review the results of the Day-Ahead and Ancillary Services markets. 1.13. “Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge” has the meaning set forth in Section 5.1(a). 1.14. “Outage” shall mean a Forecasted Planned Outage, Maintenance Outage, Unplanned Forced Outage, or a Partial Outage/Derate as such terms are defined in the PJM Governing Documents. 1.15. “PJM” shall mean PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. or its successor. 1.16. “PJM Governing Documents” shall mean the PJM Tariff, the PJM Operating Agreement, the Reliability Assurance Agreement Among Load Serving Entities in the PJM Region, and the PJM Manuals. 1.17. “PJM Manuals” shall mean PJM’s manuals that document PJM’s administrative, planning, operating, and accounting procedures. 1.18. “PJM Operating Agreement” shall mean the Amended and Restated Operating Agreement of PJM. 1.19. “PJM Tariff” shall mean the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff. 1.20. “Project Investment” or “PI” shall mean an investment made by H.A. Wagner after December 31, 2023, to enable either or both of H.A. Wagner Unit 3 and H.A. Wagner Unit 4 to continue operating for the period of time during which PJM has identified a reliability need for the Units. A Project Investment may include repairs, replacements, actions required for North American Electric Reliability Corporation or other regulatory compliance, and maintenance of Unit facilities and equipment and associated parts, supplies, labor (including overtime if consistent with Good Utility Practice), and overheads. As detailed in Section 5.2, a Project Investment may be further classified as either an “Identified Project Investment” or a “New Project Investment”. 1.21. “Rate Year” means a one-year period beginning on June 1 and ending the next May 31; provided, however, that in the event of early termination or extension of this Rate Schedule, the last Rate Year shall end as of the last date of the month in which such early termination occurs. 1.22. “RMR” means reliability must-run. 1.23. “Settlement Agreement” shall mean that certain Settlement Agreement by and among Sierra Club and Talen Energy Corporation, Montour, LLC, Brandon Shores LLC, and H.A. Wagner LLC, dated November 23, 2020 as amended April 6, 2023. 1.24. “Term” shall mean the term of this Rate Schedule as established under Section 2.2. 1.25. “Unit” or “Units” shall mean either or both of H.A. Wagner Unit 3 or H.A. Wagner Unit 4, as applicable. 2. TERM 2.1. Effective Date This Rate Schedule shall become effective June 1, 2025, or such other date as made effective by FERC. 2.2. Term of Rate Schedule Unless terminated as provided in Sections 2.3, 2.4, or 2.5, this Rate Schedule shall have a term (the “Term”) through May 31, 2029. 2.3. H.A. Wagner Termination Rights H.A. Wagner may terminate this Rate Schedule consistent with the requirements of Section 113.3 of the PJM Tariff; provided, however, H.A. Wagner agrees not to suspend or terminate this Rate Schedule prior to May 31, 2029, with respect to a Unit or any portion of a Unit (i) except as provided in Sections 2.5 and 5.2(E) or (ii) unless an event of Force Majeure has occurred that results in a Unit or any portion of a Unit not being able to continue to operate. 2.4. PJM Termination Rights a) Promptly upon determining that the H.A. Wagner Generating Station is no longer necessary for RMR service pursuant to Section 113.3 of the PJM Tariff, PJM shall provide sixty-five (65) days advanced written notice of termination to H.A. Wagner, after which sixty-five (65) day period the RMR service pursuant to this Rate Schedule shall terminate. b) In the event of such a termination for the H.A. Wagner Generating Station: (i) the applicable Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge set forth in Section 5.1 shall be reduced by forty (40) percent for the last twenty (20) days of service under this Rate Schedule and (ii) H.A. Wagner shall prepare a final invoice reflecting all amounts due to it, and including a credit for any pending proposals, consistent with Section 5.6. c) In the event of such a termination for just one of the Units of the H.A. Wagner Generating Station, then the Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge for the Unit that will continue to provide RMR service shall be determined pursuant to Section 5.1(d), and the remaining amount of the Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge set forth in Section 5.1 shall be reduced by forty (40) percent for the last twenty (20) days of service by the Unit for which RMR service is being terminated and (ii) H.A. Wagner shall prepare a final invoice reflecting all amounts due to it, including a credit for any pending proposals, consistent with Section 5.6, for that Unit. 2.5. Suspension and Other Events of Termination a) In the event operation of a Unit would violate any applicable law, regulation, or ordinance, H.A. Wagner may notify PJM that it will no longer perform under this Rate Schedule. Upon providing PJM such notice, all obligations of H.A. Wagner and PJM under this Rate Schedule shall be suspended and shall remain suspended unless and until such time as H.A. Wagner notifies PJM that it will perform again under this Rate Schedule. Notwithstanding the foregoing, H.A. Wagner shall use commercially reasonable efforts to operate the Unit(s) to avoid violation of any such applicable law, regulation or ordinance. In its sole discretion, H.A. Wagner shall not be obligated to cause any Unit to be operated in a manner that will cause it to violate the terms of any environmental restrictions or any operating permit limitations. H.A. Wagner shall use best efforts to continuously comply with all applicable permits, limitations, laws and regulations applicable to H.A. Wagner, absent any Force Majeure event. b) This Rate Schedule shall terminate ninety (90) days after any Unit becomes inoperable if PJM provides, or is deemed to have provided pursuant to Section 5.2(E), H.A. Wagner with a notice declining to approve a Project Investment. Within ten (10) days after H.A. Wagner receives, or is deemed to have received, notice that PJM has declined to approve a Project Investment pursuant to Section 5.2(E), H.A. Wagner shall provide written notice to PJM and FERC of the termination of this Rate Schedule. 2.6. Extension a) If PJM wishes to extend the Term of this Rate Schedule, PJM shall provide notice to H.A. Wagner and the intervenors in Docket No. ER24-1787-000 at least ninety (90) days prior to the date upon which PJM will post the planning parameters for the Base Residual Auction for the applicable Delivery Year. Within forty-five (45) days after receipt of PJM’s notice, but no later than seventy-five (75) days in advance of the posting of the planning parameters for the Base Residual Auction for the applicable Delivery Year, H.A. Wagner will notify PJM as to whether it will agree to continue operating if permitted to do so. If H.A. Wagner is so willing, it will provide PJM as part of the notification a status update about the potential ability to extend operations, including any additional required Project Investment needed to extend the Term of this Rate Schedule. No later than forty-five (45) days prior to the posting of the planning parameters for the Base Residual Auction for the applicable Delivery Year, H.A. Wagner shall provide its determination to PJM as to whether or not it agrees to extend the Term of this Rate Schedule, subject to PJM’s approval of required Project Investment. b) Any extension agreed to in accordance with this Section 2.6 shall be subject to H.A. Wagner filing with FERC under Federal Power Act (“FPA”) section 205 an amendment to this Rate Schedule for the rates, terms, and conditions of service during the extended term. Such amendment shall include only those changes necessary to: (i) reflect the extended term, (ii) adjust the Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge effective during the first year of the extended term to reflect an increase in labor costs from June 1, 2025, to June 1, 2029, in line with cost-of-living adjustment factors set forth in any collective bargaining agreement(s) applicable to H.A. Wagner, (iii) increase the Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge during each subsequent year of the extended term to reflect an increase in labor costs during such subsequent years of the extended term in line with cost-of-living adjustment factors set forth in any collective bargaining agreement(s) applicable to H.A. Wagner, (iv) update Section 5.2(C) to identify any Project Investment that is identified by H.A. Wagner and determined by PJM to be reasonably necessary during the extended term, and (v) make any necessary conforming changes to this Rate Schedule associated with the foregoing. 3. OBLIGATIONS 3.1. Application of PJM Governing Documents H.A. Wagner’s operation of the Units consistent with the terms and conditions of this Rate Schedule shall not be deemed inconsistent with the performance obligations identified in Section 121 of the PJM Tariff. 3.2. Scheduling and Dispatch of the Units PJM may schedule and dispatch the Units subject to the operating limitations identified in Section 3.4 and the availability of fuel, equipment, parts, and the other inputs to energy production, consisting of, but not limited to, chemicals and lubricating oils. H.A. Wagner shall undertake best efforts to cost-effectively ensure the availability of fuel, equipment, parts, and the other inputs to energy production, consisting of but not limited to, chemicals and lubricating oils. 3.3. Operation of the Units a) Subject to the terms of this Section 3.3, PJM may schedule and dispatch either or both Units solely to address (i) an identified transmission reliability need in support of the requirement to operate such transmission facilities within established thermal, voltage and stability limits under Sections 2 and 3 of PJM Manual 3 and when such transmission reliability needs cannot otherwise be met with available economically dispatched generating resources; (ii) a PJM transmission reliability need caused by a system restoration need as described in PJM Manual 36; (iii) a capacity emergency (as described in PJM Manual 13) during which PJM determines that the resources scheduled for an operating day are not sufficient to maintain the appropriate reserve levels for PJM and (iv) any required testing for either or both Units as set forth in Section 3.3(e). b) Subject to the Unit operating limitations identified in Section 3.4, H.A. Wagner shall operate either or both Units upon receipt of, and consistent with, a scheduling or dispatch notice issued by PJM. H.A. Wagner does not guarantee that such Unit(s) will start or operate at rated capacity, and H.A. Wagner does not guarantee the availability of the Unit(s) in response to a PJM scheduling or dispatch notice. c) H.A. Wagner shall not be obligated to cause either Unit to be operated in a manner that will cause H.A. Wagner to violate the terms of any law or regulation, including but not limited to any environmental restrictions or any operating permit limitations or the Settlement Agreement. d) PJM shall not issue a scheduling or dispatch notice to H.A. Wagner for operation of a Unit during periods when such Unit is unavailable due to an Outage, provided that H.A. Wagner shall notify PJM of Unit Outages consistent with the PJM Governing Documents. e) H.A. Wagner, with advance notice of at least one (1) day to, and prior approval by, PJM, may self-schedule a Unit under limited circumstances when PJM’s scheduling or dispatch of such Unit is not expected to allow necessary operational activities to occur. These activities generally include, but are not limited to, scheduling a Unit to conduct mandatory compliance testing or diagnostic evaluations performed to maintain a Unit’s ability to operate. PJM shall provide compensation pursuant to this Rate Schedule consistent with that provided during a PJM scheduling or dispatch relating to such periods of operation. f) If a Unit has not run for the prior thirty (30) days consecutively, then at the discretion of H.A. Wagner, and with prior notice to PJM, H.A. Wagner may self-schedule such Unit to operate for up to forty-eight (48) hours. If such Unit has not run for the prior thirty (30) days consecutively, PJM may, with prior notice to H.A. Wagner, schedule such Unit to operate for up to forty-eight (48) hours. PJM shall provide compensation pursuant to this Rate Schedule consistent with that provided during a PJM scheduling or dispatch relating to such periods of operation. 3.4. Operating Limitations The Units shall be coded in PJM’s Markets Gateway as Maximum-Emergency units and shall be subject to the following pre-determined limits on the offer parameters for their cost-based schedules unless different limits are approved in Markets Gateway: Parameters H.A. Wagner Unit 3 H.A. Wagner Unit 4 Minimum Down Time 24 hours 24 hours Minimum Run Time 24 hours 24 hours Maximum Daily Starts 1 1 Maximum Weekly Starts 3 3 H.A. Wagner Unit 3: Operating Parameters: Max Capacity = 305 MW Economic Max = 305 MW Economic Min = 105 MW Emergency Min = 105 MW Start-up + Notification Cold = 24 Hours Start-up + Notification Intermediate = 16 Hours Start-up + Notification Hot = 10 Hours PJM Node Name = WAGNER 13 KV GEN 03 PJM Pnode Number = 50691 H.A. Wagner Unit 4 Operating Parameters: Max Capacity = 397 MW Economic Max = 397 MW Economic Min = 60 MW Emergency Min = 60 MW Start-up + Notification Cold = 20 Hours Start-up + Notification Intermediate = 12 Hours Start-up + Notification Hot = 8 Hours PJM Node Name = WAGNER 13 KV GEN 04 PJM Pnode Number = 50692 To the extent a Unit experiences a physical operational limitation that prevents it from meeting the parameters listed above, H.A. Wagner shall modify the parameters to reflect the limitations and shall notify PJM via email and via PJM’s Electronic Dispatcher Application and Reporting Tool (“eDart”) as soon as the need for the change is recognized. Notwithstanding any operating limitations set forth in this section, H.A. Wagner shall respond to PJM scheduling and dispatch notices on a best efforts basis when consistent with law and regulation. 3.5. Obligation to Offer Units into Markets a) H.A. Wagner will submit cost-based offers of energy from the Units in the PJM Interchange Energy Market in accordance with PJM Operating Agreement, Schedule 2 and PJM Manual 15. The Units will be offered with a status of ‘unavailable’ in the PJM Interchange Energy Market but will be available to be scheduled pursuant to Section 3.3. The cost-based offer of energy also applies to scheduling and dispatch pursuant to Section 3.3(e). Costs included in the Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge pursuant to Section 5.1 and recovered for Project Investment pursuant to Section 5.2 will not be included in the Maintenance Adder (as defined in the PJM Operating Agreement) of H.A. Wagner’s cost-based offers for the Units during the Term. b) Except when the Units are unavailable due to an Outage, the Units may be offered based on their cost-based schedules into the Synchronized Reserve market when the Units are otherwise scheduled or dispatched for reliability. Such cost-based bids shall be calculated in accordance with Section 1.10.1A(j) of the PJM Operating Agreement. c) Except when the Units are unavailable due to an Outage, the Units will, when otherwise scheduled or dispatched for reliability, provide reactive power consistent with the available capability of the Unit and voltage schedules provided for in the relevant interconnection agreement. 4. SURVIVAL OF OPERATIONS AND COST RECOVERY If the provision of service pursuant to this Rate Schedule is terminated prior to the date identified in Section 2.2 and H.A. Wagner has not yet recovered costs of operating the Units under the Cost of Service Recovery Rate, which costs were incurred, H.A. Wagner shall be entitled to recover all such unrecovered costs in accordance with this Rate Schedule. If the provision of service pursuant to this Rate Schedule is terminated prior to the date identified in Section 2.2 and H.A. Wagner has not yet recovered Project Investment Costs approved by PJM, which costs were incurred, H.A. Wagner shall be entitled to recover all such costs in accordance with this Rate Schedule. 5. COST OF SERVICE RECOVERY RATE Pursuant to Section 119 of the PJM Tariff, H.A. Wagner shall recover its costs of operating H.A. Wagner Unit 3 and H.A. Wagner Unit 4 during the Term through the Cost of Service Recovery Rate identified in this Article 5. 5.1. Monthly Fixed-Cost Charges; Capacity Revenues Offset; Performance Adder a) Each month during the Term, PJM shall pay to H.A. Wagner a monthly fixed-cost charge of $2,916,667 (the “Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge”) less a hold-back of $208,333 which may be paid to H.A. Wagner in accordance with the provisions of Section 5.1(c) (the “Performance Adder Hold-Back”). b) Any Capacity Market Revenues that would otherwise be due to H.A. Wagner as a result of its Units being administratively included in a Base Residual Auction or subsequent Incremental Auctions, and clearing MW in said auction(s), shall not be paid to H.A. Wagner but shall instead be allocated by PJM to all customers paying a share of the costs under this Rate Schedule, based on those customers’ proportionate share of cost responsibility for the Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge. c) For each Rate Year during the Term, PJM shall pay to H.A. Wagner an additional amount based on the performance of the each Unit (as measured in MWh) vis à vis PJM’s dispatch requests, subject to (1) the operating limitations in Section 3.4, (2) an exemption for Force Majeure events, and (3) an exemption for any dispatch instructions that, if followed, would result in a violation of the terms of environmental restrictions or operating permit limitations (the “Performance Adder”). Such Performance Adder for each Unit shall be calculated as follows: Performance Adder = (Unit Maximum Monthly Adder x number of months in the Rate Year) x (Achieved MWh for such Unit / Dispatched MWh for such Unit), Where: “Unit Maximum Monthly Adder” means: (i) for Unit 3, $90,515 and (ii) for Unit 4, $117,818; “Achieved MWh” equals the MWh output of the Unit generated over the course of the applicable Rate Year while subject to the terms of the CORS; “Dispatched MWh” equals: (i) the MWh output of the Unit as requested by PJM dispatch instructions consistent with Section 3.4 over the course of the applicable Rate Year while subject to the terms of the CORS, less (ii) MWh requested where (1) the Unit was unable to perform due to an event of Force Majeure or (2) following the dispatch instructions would result in a violation of the terms of environmental restrictions or operating permit limitations; and For a given Rate Year, “Achieved MWh for such Unit / Dispatched MWh for such Unit” shall not exceed 100 percent. In the event the Dispatched MWh for a Unit for a given Rate Year equals zero, H.A. Wagner shall receive the full Performance Adder for such Unit for such Rate Year (equal to what it would receive had the Unit’s Achieved MWh equaled its Dispatched MWh for such Rate Year). The Performance Adder shall be included by H.A. Wagner on the first invoice tendered to PJM following the end of a Rate Year, subject to verification by PJM. d) If this Rate Schedule is terminated as to only one Unit during the Term or an extension thereof and, as a result, the fixed cost of operating the H.A. Wagner Generating Station is reduced by twenty percent (20%) or more, H.A. Wagner will consult with PJM within 60 days about the amount by which the Monthly Fixed-Cost Charge should be reduced and will submit to FERC under FPA section 205 an amendment to this Rate Schedule to reflect such reduction within 60 days thereafter. Nothing in this Rate Schedule prevents any party from filing comments or a protest in response to such FPA section 205 filing 5.2. Reimbursement of Project Investment Costs H.A. Wagner shall be entitled to reimbursement for all Project Investments that are reasonably necessary to continue to operate the Units in accordance with good utility practice, including but not limited to the Identified Project Investments listed in Section 5.2(C). PJM shall reimburse H.A. Wagner its actual costs of Project Investments undertaken pursuant to this Rate Schedule as they are incurred. Where: A. “Project Investment” shall have the meaning set forth in Article 1. B. “Project Investment Costs” shall mean costs for an Identified Project Investment or a New Project Investment. C. “Identified Project Investments” shall mean the following Project Investments: i. Units 3 and 4 Critical 4 kV Bus/Breakers Overhaul; ii. Replacement of Unit 3 Rear Wall OFA Panels 1 & 5; iii. Replacement of Unit 3 Boiler Tube Dissimilar Metal Welds; iv. Selective Replacement of Unit 3 Underground Service Water System Piping; v. Selective Replacement of Unit 4 Water Wall Tubes; vi. Structural Repairs to Unit 4 Ductwork and Hoppers; vii. Rebuild of Units 3 and 4 Bay Intake Screens and Trash Rake; viii. Units 3 and 4 Fuel Oil Tank Inspections and Repairs; and ix. Units 3 and 4 Boiler Tube and High Energy Piping Inspections and Repairs. D. “New Project Investment” shall mean any Project Investment other than one of the Identified Project Investments; provided, however, that if and to the extent the total costs of the Identified Project Investments exceed $4.5 million ($4,500,000), the amount in excess of this figure will be considered a “New Project Investment.” E. If it is necessary to undertake a New Project Investment to enable one or both Units to continue to operate during the remaining Term, and the cost of a New Project Investment is expected to be in excess of $100,000, H.A. Wagner shall notify and consult with PJM in writing, and provide detailed support to identify the nature of the New Project Investment and the expected duration and associated New Project Investment Costs (“New PI Support”). Within fifteen (15) days of receipt of H.A. Wagner’ notice, PJM shall notify H.A. Wagner in writing of the need to undertake the subject New Project Investment to support the reliable operation of the PJM Transmission System. During the fifteen (15) day-time period, the Performance Adder Hold-Back set forth in Section 5.1(a) shall not apply. If PJM notifies H.A. Wagner that it declines to approve such New Project Investment, then the subject New Project Investment will not be undertaken and H.A. Wagner may provide notice of termination pursuant to Section 2.3(b). If within twenty (20) days of receipt of H.A. Wagner’ written notice with respect to a New Project Investment, PJM fails to notify H.A. Wagner in writing whether it approves or declines to approve such New Project Investment, PJM will be deemed to have provided H.A. Wagner notice declining to approve such New Project Investment and H.A. Wagner may provide notice pursuant to Section 2.3(b). In the event such notice is provided, the Performance Adder Hold-Back set forth in Section 5.1(a) shall not apply. H.A. Wagner shall not be required to provide notice in advance of any New Project Investment with a cost not expected to exceed $100,000, but, as soon as practicable after deciding to initiate a project with costs below this threshold, will provide notice to PJM and to the list in Section 7, such notice to include the estimated New Project Investment Costs and an explanation of the need for the New Project Investment. New Project Investments undertaken in accordance with this Paragraph G shall be added to the Unamortized Project Investment Costs when accrued. All notices from H.A. Wagner and PJM that are required under this Section 5.2(E) shall be distributed to the list in Section 7, at the time such notices are otherwise provided. F. Project Investment Costs shall be recovered on the basis of actual costs incurred. Not later than ninety (90) days after the end of the Term, H.A. Wagner shall report to PJM the actual amounts expended for the projects pursuant to this Rate Schedule. Not later than sixty (60) days after submission of such report to PJM, H.A. Wagner will refund any amount by which the Project Investment Costs reimbursed to H.A. Wagner exceed actual expenditures or will charge PJM any amount by which actual expenditures exceed the amount of the Project Investment Costs previously paid to H.A. Wagner. G. Project Investment Costs will be billed monthly and paid in full by PJM in the month after invoicing as set forth in Section 5.6 herein. 5.3. Potential Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement In the event that Project Investment enables H.A. Wagner to remain operational beyond the Term, and H.A. Wagner continues to operate beyond the Term and is not subject to a RMR-type rate schedule or agreement, H.A. Wagner shall refund to PJM a share of the amount of any Project Investment for which it received reimbursement pursuant to this Rate Schedule as set forth in Section 5.2. The Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement shall be determined using the following formula: Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement = [Project Investment (PI) Cost / Number of months PI permits H.A. Wagner to operate, capped at the number of months between the in-service date of the PI and the date H.A. Wagner ceases to operate (whether subject to a RMR-type rate schedule or agreement, or otherwise)] * [Number of months PI permits H.A. Wagner to operate, capped at the number of months between the in-service date of the PI and the date H.A. Wagner ceases to operate (whether subject to a RMR-type rate schedule or agreement, or otherwise) - the number of months during the Term in which the PI was in service], Where: 1) The number of months the Project Investment allows H.A. Wagner to operate as determined by H.A. Wagner and verified by PJM. 2) H.A. Wagner shall make the Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement each month for the number of months a Project Investment permits H.A. Wagner to continue to operate beyond the Term, and continues to operate beyond the Term not subject to a RMR-type rate schedule or agreement, and shall be credited to transmission customers in such month on the same basis as costs are allocated under Section 120 of the PJM Tariff, for as many months as H.A. Wagner continues to operate beyond the Term of this Rate Schedule. This Section shall be interpreted in a manner consistent with Section 118 of the PJM Tariff except for the substitution “of the number of months during the Term in which the Project Investment was placed in-service” for “the number of months during the Term” in the Refund of Project Investment Reimbursement equation, above. To assist in such interpretation, the following examples illustrate the correct application of this proposal: Formula Component Variable Example 1 Example 2 Example 3 Project Investment (PI) Cost W $1,000,000 $1,000,000 $1,000,000 Number of months PI permits H.A. Wagner to operate, capped at the number of months between the in-service date of the PI and the date H.A. Wagner ceases to operate (whether subject to a RMR-type rate schedule or agreement, or otherwise) X 60 90 60 Number of months during the Term in which the PI was in service Y 4 4 24 Number of months the PI allows H.A. Wagner to operate, and H.A. Wagner does operate, past the end of the Term of this Rate Schedule X – Y 56 86 36 Monthly refund of PI Reimbursement W / X $16,666.67 $11,111.11 $16,666.67 Months of Project Reimbursement X – Y 56 86 36
5.4. Reimbursement of Fuel and Variable Operations and Maintenance Costs For each month during the Term, PJM shall reimburse H.A. Wagner any costs incurred in the operation of the Units not otherwise recovered in an amount calculated in accordance with the following methodologies. a) Fuel Costs. Fuel costs will be determined based on actual costs, using a weighted average inventory methodology. Fuel costs will include all necessary costs associated with securing fuel (regardless of when incurred), including but not limited to delivery costs, taxes, fees, and costs associated with any letters of credit needed to purchase fuel, including startup fuel and fuel used to operate auxiliary boilers to provide steam necessary to start the Units 3 and 4, as well as fuel for the H.A. Wagner Combustion Turbine necessary to provide emergency station power. No later than sixty (60) days prior to the expiration of this Rate Schedule, H.A. Wagner shall inform PJM of fuel inventory levels, and PJM may dispatch the Units to decrease fuel inventory levels prior to the end of the Term. If fuel is remaining at the end of the Term, H.A. Wagner will undertake reasonable commercial efforts to sell such remaining fuel, and PJM will reimburse H.A. Wagner its actual costs of the fuel and removal costs less the sales price of the remaining fuel. H.A. Wagner shall invoice PJM for removal costs monthly as incurred. If the inventory costs exceed the resale proceeds received by H.A. Wagner, then H.A. Wagner shall invoice PJM for the difference in the month after any such resale occurs. Relevant fuels include (i) No. 4 Fuel Oil – Primary fuel for Unit 3 and Unit 4 and (ii) Natural Gas – Start-up fuel used for ignition in Units 3 and 4 and for operating auxiliary boilers to provide steam for starting Units 3 and 4. b) Emissions and Environmental Costs. Emissions costs will be determined based on actual costs, using the monthly average price of emissions, in $/ton as published in the Argus Air Daily. The emissions with respect to which H.A. Wagner may recover its costs include, but are not limited to, the following: A. NOx emissions allowances, B. SO2 emissions allowances, C. CO2 emissions allowances, D. Nitrogen discharge allowances, E. Maryland State Renewable Energy Credits for any retail purchases of electricity necessary to operate the Units during the Term, and F. Any additional items required by changes in law, regulation, or permit conditions. c) Chemicals Costs. Chemicals costs will be determined based on actual costs. At the end of the Term, PJM will pay for actual costs and removal costs less the sales price of the remaining chemicals and bulk lubricating oils. Any net revenues received by H.A. Wagner for the sale of unused chemicals shall be credited against Fuel and Variable Operations and Maintenance Costs to be recovered by H.A. Wagner. Chemicals costs shall include, but are not limited to: A. Urea (SCR NOx Control Chemical), B. Sulfuric Acid, Caustic (Boiler Water Control), C. Sulfuric Acid, Hydrochloric Acid, Hydrated Lime (WWTP Chemicals), and D. Bulk Lubricating Oils and disposal. d) Auxiliary Power. Auxiliary or standby (i.e., station) power costs will not be included in the Fuel and Variable Operations and Maintenance Costs submitted by H.A. Wagner. Auxiliary power costs will be billed pursuant to PJM Tariff, Attachment K-Appendix and will be reimbursed via inclusion of such station power costs in the Revenue Credits detailed in Section 5.6. e) Regulatory and Administrative Costs. In the first Rate Year, H.A. Wagner may include recovery of up to $2,700,000 in regulatory and administrative costs, such costs to include, but not be limited to, the costs of obtaining a final FERC order, and any associated appeals, accepting this Rate Schedule for filing. 5.5. Revenue Credits For service provided during the Term, H.A. Wagner will credit monthly net revenues (total credits net of total charges), identified on the applicable PJM bill earned from any sales of wholesale energy, capacity and ancillary services from a Unit or other revenues earned with respect to a Unit during the Term, each as earned in PJM’s markets or pursuant to other rate schedules on file with FERC, against the charges under Sections 5.1, 5.2, and 5.4 above and will provide an invoice reflecting this credit pursuant to Section 5.6 below. If such monthly net revenues are positive and exceed the monthly charges under Sections 5.1, 5.2 and 5.4, any amount in excess of those monthly charges shall be credited back to all customers paying a share of the costs under this Rate Schedule and charged to H.A. Wagner. If the monthly net revenues are less than zero, those negative net revenues shall be added to the charges under Sections 5.1, 5.2 and 5.4 and increase the amount payable to H.A. Wagner. 5.6. Invoices a) Monthly Invoicing H.A. Wagner will issue a monthly invoice to PJM for the amounts due under Sections 5.1, 5.2, and 5.4. Such invoice shall reflect as a separate line item the revenue credits for each Unit provided for in Section 5.5. H.A. Wagner will issue the invoice no later than the fifteenth (15th) calendar day of the month following the month in which service is provided, unless extenuating circumstances exist, in which case it will issue the invoice no later than the last business day of the month. Upon request, H.A. Wagner will provide supporting data to PJM for such invoice. Project Investment costs are subject to the true-up process at the end of the Term as set forth in Section 5.2(H). PJM shall include the charges billed by H.A. Wagner in the PJM monthly billing statement for the month in which PJM received the invoice from H.A. Wagner (for example: April invoice is received in May and goes out in the PJM monthly bill for May). PJM shall remit payment to H.A. Wagner according to the standard financial settlement timeline for such PJM monthly billing statement. Such invoices shall also include as separate line items any adjustments to previously billed amounts. Upon request, H.A. Wagner will provide supporting data for such invoice. b) Final Invoicing Except as otherwise provided in Sections 5.1 and 5.2(H), not later than ninety (90) days from the end of the Term, H.A. Wagner will issue final invoices for amounts due under this Rate Schedule. However, notwithstanding any provision of this Rate Schedule to the contrary, should costs incurred to provide service pursuant to this Rate Schedule continue to be incurred after the end of the Term, or should fuel inventory or Consumables take longer to liquidate, the final invoices shall be due within ninety (90) days from the last date cost incurrence ceases or fuel and Consumables are fully liquidated. 6. MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS a) PJM and H.A. Wagner may by mutual agreement waive any of the time periods set forth herein that apply exclusively to PJM and H.A. Wagner. b) References to PJM Governing Documents included herein shall be to the versions in effect as of the Effective Date, as they may be amended from time to time. c) To the extent H.A. Wagner is prevented by Force Majeure from carrying out, in whole or part, its obligations under this Rate Schedule and it gives notice and details of the Force Majeure to PJM as soon as practicable, then H.A. Wagner shall be excused from the performance of its obligations with respect to this Rate Schedule to the extent prevented by such Force Majeure. H.A. Wagner shall remedy the Force Majeure with all reasonable dispatch. d) Any labor performed hereunder will be governed by and construed, enforced, and performed in accordance with the terms of any current collective bargaining agreement between Talen Energy Corporation and the International Brotherhood of the Electrical Workers. e) Notwithstanding any provision in the PJM Tariff to the contrary, H.A. Wagner shall not be subject to any capacity-related penalties (capacity deficiency or non-performance penalties, e.g., penalties for non-performance during Performance Assessment Intervals), bonuses, or the like during the Term, nor shall H.A. Wagner be required to offer capacity or energy into any PJM market or auction in any manner except as provided in Section 3.5. f) All references herein to a “Section” shall mean the Section of this Rate Schedule, unless the context specifies otherwise. 7. DESIGNATED REPRESENTATIVES For purposes of any notices required to be provided pursuant hereto, notice shall be provided by electronic mail and the designated representatives to receive such notices shall be: For H.A. Wagner: Jennifer Mansh Jennifer.Mansh @talenenergy.com For PJM: Thomas DeVita Thomas.DeVita@pjm.com For Maryland Public Service Commission Andrew Johnston, Executive Secretary Andrew.Johnston@maryland.gov
For Old Dominion Electric Cooperative Michael Cocco MCocco@odec.com
For Southern Maryland Electric Cooperative, Inc. Damon Krieger damon.krieger@smeco.com
For Exelon Corporation Gary Guy Gary.Guy@exeloncorp.com
Any entity may change its respective designated representative by written notice to all other designated representatives. 8. STANDARD OF REVIEW The standard of review for changes to any rate, charge, classification, term or condition of this Rate Schedule, whether proposed by PJM, any party with standing under Federal Power Act Section 206, or FERC acting sua sponte, shall solely be the most stringent standard of review set forth in United Gas Pipe Line Co. v. Mobile Gas Service Corp., 350 U.S. 332 (1956) and Federal Power Commission v. Sierra Pacific Power Co., 350 U.S. 348 (1956) and clarified by Morgan Stanley Capital Group, Inc. v. Public Util. Dist. No. 1 of Snohomish, 554 U.S. 527, 128 S. Ct. 2733 (2008) and NRG Power Marketing, LLC, et al. v. Maine Public Utilities Commission, 558 U.S. 165 (2010), as clarified by Devon Power LLC, 134 FERC ¶ 61,208 (2011).
